{
  "answer": "**Zauq's rind-couplet** (from the opening sher of his ghazal explicitly titled after the \"rind-e-kharaab-haal,\" or ruined libertine):  \n\n> O pious judge, don't mock this ruined soul with your disdain;  \n> Just settle your accounts with God, and leave me to my pain.[^1]  \n\nHere, the rind is a spiritually ravaged figure—personally \"ruined\" (*kharab*) by love or ecstasy—directly rebuking the zahid (pious hypocrite) and invoking divine judgment, embodying the classic Sufi antithesis of outward piety versus inward divine intoxication.[^2]\n\n**Ghalib's rind-couplet** (from a ghazal contrasting the maikada/tavern with piety):  \n\n> O pious man, the tavern's revelers are coarse and bold;  \n> Don't mix with them, I'm weary of the judgments they despise.[^3]  \n\nGhalib's rinds (*rindaan-e-dar-e-maikada*) are rowdy tavern-goers, defiantly \"coarse\" and dismissive of social/religious norms in a public, boisterous setting.[^4]\n\n**Comparison**: Zauq's rind is the more *theological* figure—a solitary soul in mystical ruin, urging the zahid toward God and personal reckoning, deeply embedded in Sufi zahid-rind typology. Ghalib's is more *social*—a collective of brash, worldly drinkers clashing with piety in the tavern's communal chaos, emphasizing irreverence amid human gatherings over private divine accounting.\n\n[^1]: Sheikh Ibrahim Zauq, *Diwan-E-Zauq*, [46-rind-e-kharaab-haal-ko-zaahid-na-chhed-tu/translation/#p-0083db](https://falsafa.corpus/works/sheikh-ibrahim-zauq-diwan-e-zauq-0fa798/46-rind-e-kharaab-haal-ko-zaahid-na-chhed-tu/translation/#p-0083db).\n[^2]: Sheikh Ibrahim Zauq, *Diwan-E-Zauq*, [46-rind-e-kharaab-haal-ko-zaahid-na-chhed-tu/translation/](https://falsafa.corpus/works/sheikh-ibrahim-zauq-diwan-e-zauq-0fa798/46-rind-e-kharaab-haal-ko-zaahid-na-chhed-tu/translation/).\n[^3]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [61-hai-bazm-e-butaan-mein-sukhan-aazurda-labon-se/translation/#p-d0f118](https://falsafa.corpus/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/61-hai-bazm-e-butaan-mein-sukhan-aazurda-labon-se/translation/#p-d0f118).\n[^4]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [61-hai-bazm-e-butaan-mein-sukhan-aazurda-labon-se/translation/](https://falsafa.corpus/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/61-hai-bazm-e-butaan-mein-sukhan-aazurda-labon-se/translation/).",
